  <box id="noun">
    <title><mark>fad</mark> as a de-adjectival noun</title>
    <p>The most straightforward use of <strong>fad</strong> is as an abstract noun meaning <en>length</en>, derived from the gradable adjective <strong><a href="?gd=fada">fada</a></strong>
      <en>long</en>. For example –</p>
    <xl>
      <li>2938</li>
    </xl>
  </box>

  <box id="air_fad">
    <title>air fad</title>
    <p>The prepositional phrase <strong>air fad</strong> is a postnominal modifier which modifies a definite noun, with the meaning <en>all, whole</en>. For example –</p>
    <xl>
      <li>3289</li>
      <li>3291</li>
      <li>3328</li>
    </xl>
  </box>

  <box id="all_over">
    <title><mark>fad</mark> as a spatial preposition</title>
    <p> For example –</p>
    <xl>
      <li>3343</li>
    </xl>
  </box>


  <box id="preposition-indefinite">
    <title><mark>fad</mark> as a preposition of temporal extent – indefinite uses</title>
    <p><strong>fad</strong> can be used as (reduced compound) preposition introducing an adverbial phrase of temporal extent, describing the duration of a state or activity. When <strong>fad</strong>
      governs an <em>indefinite</em> temporal interval noun, it means something like English <en>for</en>.</p>
