      <li>2935</li>
      <li>2937</li>
      <li>3281</li>
      <li>3339</li>
      <li>3322</li>
      <li>3330</li>
    </xl>
    <p>Note the following examples with a plural noun –</p>
    <xl>
      <li>3341</li>
      <li>3346</li>
    </xl>
  </box>

  <box id="conjunction-imperfective">
    <title><mark>fhad ’s a</mark> as a conjunction of temporal extent</title>
    <p><strong>fad</strong> can be used as a kind of subordinating conjunction, introducing an imperfective temporal adverbial clause describing the time period over which some other situation
      extends, or within which an action happens. In this sense, <strong>fad</strong> is usually lenited and conjoined using a contracted version of <strong>agus</strong>
      <en>and</en> with a relative clause, i.e. <strong>fhad ’s a (tha)</strong>.</p>
    <p>When the conjunction <strong>fhad ’s a</strong> introduces a temporal adverbial which modifies an <em>imperfective</em> state or activity, it corresponds to the English conjunctions <en>as long
